WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:28.000
The

00:28.000 --> 00:37.560
Metacrisis is the historically specific threat to truth, beauty, and goodness caused by our

00:37.560 --> 00:46.480
persistent misunderstanding, misvaluing, and misappropriing of reality. It arises from the

00:46.480 --> 00:54.800
material and spiritual exhaustion of modernity. It is a multifaceted delusion. It is the crisis

00:54.800 --> 01:03.680
within, between, and beyond our existing conceptual crisis, and it manifests institutionally and

01:03.680 --> 01:12.920
culturally to the detriment of life on earth. The Metacrisis is something about our relationship

01:12.920 --> 01:17.040
to all of the crises in the world. So it's reflexive, it's inherently reflexive, it's about

01:17.040 --> 01:23.840
talking through, thinking through, how does human nature relate to this thing. Now, that's quite

01:23.840 --> 01:29.120
distinct from polycrisis, or permanent crisis, or all these other terms. What's different about

01:29.120 --> 01:34.160
Metacrisis is it acknowledges human interiority and relationality as a fundamental part of the

01:34.160 --> 01:38.960
problem, or the problematic, I should say. The other way of looking at Metacrisis, and there are

01:38.960 --> 01:45.480
many actually, but you can see it as the sign that modernity is ending. And so this expression of

01:45.480 --> 01:52.760
Zack Stein's time between worlds, that we're in a time between worlds captures that. And it's

01:52.800 --> 01:56.000
because we're in a time between worlds that things don't make sense, things begin to break

01:56.000 --> 02:01.280
down. And this is where, again, you can get into Jean Gebster's notion of the mental rational

02:01.280 --> 02:06.400
function, breaking down, which in plain language is intellectually we're not up to it anymore. The

02:06.400 --> 02:11.760
intellectual function is not succeeding in making sense of the world. The world is eclipsing or

02:11.760 --> 02:17.120
going beyond our capacity to make sense of it. And these are all signs that our existing form of

02:17.120 --> 02:23.640
consciousness is somehow in need of evolution, in need of growing in some way. But I also think

02:23.640 --> 02:29.840
Meta's kind of alive. I think there's a kind of participatory knowing of the Metacrisis. When

02:29.840 --> 02:33.880
you put it as a proposition, and say define the Metacrisis, it becomes one more concept,

02:33.880 --> 02:40.040
a million concepts. The Metacrisis is your daily experience of a world falling apart. It's your

02:40.040 --> 02:46.000
incredulity towards how weird everything's becoming. Both the kind of rapid technological growth,

02:46.880 --> 02:53.680
and the combination of synthetic biology and AI and virtual reality, changing the life world. And

02:53.680 --> 02:59.840
then you have things like gene editing and so on that are actually changing life as such. And then

02:59.840 --> 03:05.920
you have maybe a new phase of geological time. The academics are still arguing about it. But for

03:05.920 --> 03:11.920
all intents and purposes, the whole of scene has ended. The stable geological period that has lasted

03:11.920 --> 03:18.960
many thousands of years is now unstable. And we're entering uncharted territory. And you can see

03:18.960 --> 03:27.640
that in the planetary boundary framework very clearly. But you can also feel it. The quick

03:27.640 --> 03:33.240
definition would be something like the Metacrisis is all the crisis put together, right? And people

03:33.240 --> 03:37.240
go, Oh, I see, I see. But they don't see, right? Because it's not really the end of it. That's

03:37.240 --> 03:42.520
just the beginning of the conversation. The Metacrisis is also in the way you make sense of the

03:42.520 --> 03:50.720
world, the way you feel it and in a mode in relation to it. The Metacrisis is in your incapacitated,

03:50.720 --> 03:59.920
fully articulate and narrate the self in this context. And the Metacrisis is also, you know,

03:59.920 --> 04:06.920
co extensive with co arising with this particular historical epoch. So it's not as though there

04:06.960 --> 04:12.240
haven't been Metacrisis before. I mean, arguably, the time of Christ was a kind of Metacrisis. If

04:12.240 --> 04:19.080
you think about an occupying Roman Empire, a kind of religious fervor people waiting for, you know,

04:19.080 --> 04:25.320
Messiah, and then this person appears apparently doing miracles. Everyone's totally confused, right?

04:25.320 --> 04:31.600
Just as we are kind of now. So one of many examples where it's not like we haven't had historical

04:31.640 --> 04:37.800
turbulence before. Is there something distinct about today? Yes, that we're actually destroying our

04:37.800 --> 04:45.640
only home. Our one precious planet in the infinite regions of space is under threat, not of annihilation

04:45.640 --> 04:52.120
necessarily, but of being in a habitat for human life. That's in question now. The forms of

04:52.120 --> 04:57.800
technology developing so rapidly that you can get into a world of autonomous weapons that really

04:57.800 --> 05:04.160
can cause massive destruction. So what's different today is the degree of risk to the planet as a

05:04.160 --> 05:13.240
whole. That's one distinct feature of the Metacrisis. But arguably we had this with nuclear weapons as

05:13.240 --> 05:20.320
well. So it's different. But at the same time, I like to speak of the Metacrisis in a way that

05:20.320 --> 05:28.120
doesn't just leave you dazed and confused, and looking as a passive subject at a kind of unfamiliar

05:28.120 --> 05:35.560
object saying, that there is the Metacrisis. What do I do? That's not the way to go. The Metacrisis is

05:35.560 --> 05:42.040
our historical inheritance. We're born into this. It's this generation that perceives it and feels

05:42.040 --> 05:47.240
it. It's the set of cards we have to play. It's not something we can fix. The problem with the

05:47.240 --> 05:53.240
crisis framing is that it's still a kind of tacit problem solution mentality. That would be

05:53.240 --> 05:58.400
misunderstanding the nature of the Metacrisis. What's going on is a very slow historical process

05:58.400 --> 06:05.080
that's culminating in a certain way and beginning to transform into something else. The nature of

06:05.080 --> 06:12.600
what it transforms into will depend whether we survive and thrive or collapse. I believe about 90%

06:12.840 --> 06:17.040
of what I just said. But there's another part of me that says, are we sure this is the time between

06:17.040 --> 06:23.480
worlds? Is modernity really ending? If I told Elon Musk or Sam Altman that modernity is ending,

06:23.480 --> 06:29.640
they'd just laugh at me, right? So I'm thinking of the other side saying, modernity is not ending.

06:29.640 --> 06:34.880
What are you talking about? It's just taking off. If anything, technology is going to radically

06:34.880 --> 06:39.040
change the world and solve a lot of these problems. Now, I don't feel that. It's not how I'm politically,

06:39.120 --> 06:46.360
socially, culturally, intellectually oriented, but it's possible. It's possible that you solve

06:46.360 --> 06:53.360
something like nuclear fusion and have abundant energy. It's conceivable that a lot of the

06:53.360 --> 06:59.800
illnesses that lead us to suffer and die will be dealt with. It's conceivable that the powers that

06:59.800 --> 07:07.120
be that somehow at the moment seems so cut off from the rest of the world will be in some sense

07:07.200 --> 07:13.920
democratized and brought back into the fold such that the great benefits that are currently accruing

07:13.920 --> 07:19.920
in a very small number of people are shared more widely and people might insist on that. So I'm

07:19.920 --> 07:32.280
not sort of predisposed to feel that collapse is sort of absolutely necessary. On the other hand,

07:32.320 --> 07:39.800
I do feel a kind of collapse is underway. And the challenge for us is collapse is underway. What

07:39.800 --> 07:46.560
does a transformative response to collapse look like? But look, I say this in a kitchen in a

07:46.560 --> 07:54.320
suburb of Landa, living quite a full, healthy life in a safe, democratic, more or less country.

07:55.240 --> 08:03.800
So there's a lot of incredulity here. There's a lot of dissonance, confusion that we live as if

08:03.800 --> 08:09.040
living a normal life while watching the news in our pocket, the kind of planet in our pocket that

08:09.040 --> 08:15.000
says everything's falling apart. And yet we go to the shop and we buy our milk and we walk back home

08:15.720 --> 08:22.680
as if things are normal. So that's kind of the Metacrisis too. It's the experience of

08:23.800 --> 08:31.240
confusion that's now baked into our lives as we hear about a world collapsing on the news and on

08:31.240 --> 08:40.120
our phones, but often live as if life could carry on forever. I was formed as many, many millions

08:40.200 --> 08:46.440
of people were with a notion of what normal looks like. And a lot of what's going on is a kind of

08:46.440 --> 08:52.240
clamouring to get normal back, like solve these problems, you know, like make them make democracy

08:52.240 --> 08:59.680
stronger, make the market work, but just get rid of the environmental externalities. You know,

08:59.680 --> 09:04.320
yes, there's problems with, you know, mass immigration, but surely we can just build more

09:04.360 --> 09:11.280
houses and, you know, there's a kind of notion that make do and mend is enough, right? But many

09:11.280 --> 09:14.920
don't feel that in their hearts, right? Many feel this is something altogether different.

09:14.920 --> 09:21.600
Now, I think what's going on in our kind of community in our world is that most people are

09:21.600 --> 09:27.200
reading the position and seeing that the make do and mend story doesn't doesn't sound like it's

09:27.200 --> 09:36.280
true. It seems very unlikely. It seems more likely that they'll either be in the next years,

09:36.280 --> 09:43.040
decades, hard to say exactly how quickly, but forms of dissolution and collapse in various

09:43.040 --> 09:48.480
parts of the world, you know, you're already seeing people dying of heat deaths and people

09:48.480 --> 09:54.520
losing their homes to floods and forest fires. And we don't, we haven't really seen AI biting

09:54.520 --> 09:59.920
properly yet on the labor market, but that will begin to happen. And we see deep fakes

09:59.920 --> 10:05.480
affecting democratic elections. And that will happen more like the Nobel Prize winner Maria

10:05.480 --> 10:12.160
Ressa feels that 2024 will be the last year of proper democratic elections, because she sees the

10:12.160 --> 10:16.520
problem of these technologies basically, you can't trust public opinion that the notion of

10:16.520 --> 10:22.640
universal suffrage is compromised by the fact that the information stream is polluted with

10:22.880 --> 10:29.720
falsehoods. And so the legitimacy that underpins democracy is in question, right? And so you get

10:29.720 --> 10:35.360
problems with authoritarianism and so on. If that seems confusing, it's because it is. It's

10:35.360 --> 10:41.080
because all these things are happening at once. Most people in our sector of the internet and our

10:41.080 --> 10:48.200
sort of world feel intuitively that something deeper is going on. And we look to history sometimes

10:48.240 --> 10:54.400
to see what is this like? What kind of transition is this like? And there are many ways of doing it,

10:54.400 --> 11:00.000
but one would be the Axial Age. One would just say there was a moment in time about give or

11:00.000 --> 11:06.640
take 500 years before Christ, where there was the early signs of systematic thought,

11:06.640 --> 11:14.520
that we sort of moved out of a kind of mythos into a kind of logos, where we began to actually have

11:15.520 --> 11:24.680
sort of reason and writing. And we would turn from a barter economy to money and there was a

11:24.680 --> 11:30.520
move towards the cities away from the country. And in our consciousness, the sort of notion of the

11:30.520 --> 11:38.200
individual was kind of born. And then at this time, Buddha appeared and Lao Tzu and so on,

11:38.200 --> 11:45.760
and many of the Greek philosophers. And around that time, it was as if the whole world, although

11:45.760 --> 11:52.360
it wasn't evenly spread, developed a new kind of consciousness. And I think a lot of people in my

11:52.360 --> 11:57.160
world feel something else like that as happening. And it's a very audacious, somewhat absurd thing

11:57.160 --> 12:04.040
to think. But it roughly is what I think. It feels more true than that we can muddle through with

12:04.040 --> 12:09.560
the existing framework. So when people ask me what I'm doing sometimes, because I did a lot of work

12:09.560 --> 12:14.480
on climate change, I have a lot of contacts in that world. And they're working on, you know,

12:14.480 --> 12:21.040
getting the government to sign up to net zero by 2030 or whatever the latest thing is. And I'm like,

12:21.040 --> 12:25.960
well, you can do that if you like. But I think something altogether deeper is happening. And

12:25.960 --> 12:33.800
you're not likely to succeed that way. I place more hope in a fundamental transformation of

12:33.800 --> 12:38.560
consciousness than I do in dealing with things with the institutional and cultural structure we

12:38.560 --> 12:43.960
have now. It's worth saying a bit more about Time Between Worlds, because it's, like I say,

12:43.960 --> 12:50.680
the expression was first mooted in a book titled by Zachary Stein called Education in a Time

12:50.680 --> 12:55.680
Between Worlds. And the term is very charming. And so people use it as a shorthand for this

12:55.680 --> 13:01.960
period of time. But it's important to understand that it has precursors. So in sociology, particularly

13:01.960 --> 13:07.120
in Gramsci, there's this notion of the interregnum, where one thing has ended, but the next thing

13:07.120 --> 13:18.240
hasn't yet been born. In anthropology, there's the notion of the liminal, which is really

13:18.240 --> 13:22.880
fascinating for our community. Because what it is to be in the liminal is for an ethnographer,

13:22.880 --> 13:29.440
who is from one culture, let's say a regular Western culture, goes into a tribal context or

13:30.040 --> 13:36.240
an indigenous context. And he's trying to do deep ethnographic work. So he's trying to sort of

13:36.240 --> 13:42.760
live like them with them, observe them, participate or observation. But there's a period of time

13:42.760 --> 13:47.040
when they're neither, they're so ensconced in that world that they almost forget what it was like

13:47.040 --> 13:52.160
to be in the prior world. But they're not yet one of them. And that's what they mean by liminal

13:52.160 --> 13:56.720
anthropology. And in some ways, that's how a lot of our community is. It's like we don't

13:56.800 --> 14:02.680
entirely belong to the world as it is now, although we're still part of it. And yet there

14:02.680 --> 14:06.760
isn't really another thing that we're fully belonging in. So we're in this in between phase.

14:06.760 --> 14:11.840
The other thing to say about time between worlds is it's not just a poetic soundbite. There's

14:11.840 --> 14:17.880
quite a lot of empirical work underpinning it. So Immanuel Wallerstein's world system dynamics

14:17.880 --> 14:23.400
is one of these sources. And that's to do with understanding the world system as trade flows.

14:23.680 --> 14:28.720
And it's actually a very political analysis. It's to do with the exploitation of the poor world

14:28.720 --> 14:34.680
by the rich world. And following the pattern of that over time, and seeing that it lacks durability,

14:34.680 --> 14:39.120
that it will inevitably collapse. And then you have work by people like Peter Turchin to do a

14:39.120 --> 14:44.000
secular psycho theory. It's some similar theory of history. He sometimes calls it cleodynamics,

14:44.000 --> 14:48.480
which is the sort of quantitative history of looking at past patterns and seeing how they repeat

14:48.520 --> 14:56.200
today, and measuring things like income inequality, and autocratic governance, and so on. And

14:56.200 --> 15:00.480
beginning to sort of do a quantitative measure when this number of things happen, things fall

15:00.480 --> 15:04.680
apart. So the time between worlds is not just a feeling. There's also a kind of empirical

15:04.680 --> 15:12.360
underpinning to it. And at its heart, there's an analysis of modernity. And what the hell is

15:12.360 --> 15:19.760
that, right? I'm not sure I can adequately describe modernity, but Habermas speaks of it as an

15:19.760 --> 15:25.480
orientation towards the future. And a big part of what's happening in our world is, people are not

15:25.480 --> 15:31.280
so sure about the future. It's not clear where the ship is sailing, where we're going, right? So

15:31.280 --> 15:35.760
to be in a time between worlds in that sense, and the reason some people call it meta-modern,

15:36.040 --> 15:43.640
is that if the orientation to the future and the progress narrative is a big part of what

15:43.640 --> 15:49.080
modernity is about, first of all, we can't see the future very clearly. And if anything,

15:49.080 --> 15:54.120
we're a bit wary of it. And secondly, it's not at all clear its progress. It might well be regress.

15:54.120 --> 15:59.880
And that's why it's between worlds. And then you also have, though, rather than just the world is

15:59.880 --> 16:04.880
me, everything's falling apart. There are these wellsprings of renewal. You know, there are these

16:04.880 --> 16:10.800
people doing different things, like I'm thinking here of maybe Joe Brewer, who's currently trying to

16:10.800 --> 16:16.680
get a river back to life in Bari-Chara, Colombia. And that's exciting because he's kind of given up

16:16.680 --> 16:23.240
on the nation state. He's like, we need to start building the biorhegional hubs. And then there

16:23.240 --> 16:27.040
are many biorhegions around the world. If more people start to work around biorhegions, you might

16:27.040 --> 16:32.120
find a new form of governance emerging. Then you have this notion of like cosmolocalism, which

16:32.160 --> 16:37.400
is something to do with being wise about your production patterns, so that if something is very

16:37.400 --> 16:43.800
heavy to transport, you don't transport it. You use it locally. But also, it's more philosophically,

16:43.800 --> 16:49.280
it's kind of like you focus locally on your niche and your immediate needs in your community. But

16:49.280 --> 16:54.440
you're connected to this much bigger cosmological framework because of the internet. And you have

16:54.440 --> 16:59.960
other ideas, you know, there's ontological mutiny. It's a term of biocomalaphism, that we somehow

17:00.000 --> 17:05.160
have to just break out of this kind of collective illusion that we're part of. My colleague,

17:05.160 --> 17:10.520
Evo Mensch also speaks about this. He jokes that we're collectively living a life that no longer

17:10.520 --> 17:16.640
exists. And a lot of us feel that way. When Bonita has work on complex potential states, something to

17:16.640 --> 17:24.680
do with inshooting potentials, quite a Taoist go with the energy kind of notion. So it's not as

17:24.680 --> 17:29.840
though there's no ideas. It's not as though no one has any idea what happens next. But if you look

17:29.880 --> 17:36.240
at scale, in terms of where the power is, who has power now, particularly technological power, it

17:36.240 --> 17:43.520
is daunting. And it takes quite a lot of courage and resilience, not to just give in to despair.

17:46.520 --> 17:52.080
I came across it through my friend Zachary Stein, and I think he worked on it with Mark

17:52.080 --> 17:57.800
Gaffney. And it's to do with what they call the stations of the self. And it's not really a

17:57.840 --> 18:04.080
developmental theory, but it's more a way of describing a sort of existential interiority of

18:04.080 --> 18:10.480
the human being as it goes through life. And the stages are roughly pre-tragic, tragic, and

18:10.480 --> 18:15.920
post-tragic. Pre-tragic is something like we can fix every problem. Everything's going to be okay.

18:16.000 --> 18:21.520
Don't don't fixate on your worries. Everything will work out in the end. We can do it kind of

18:21.520 --> 18:28.200
in our mentality. So arguably a lot of techno optimism is pre-tragic. It's sort of like not

18:28.200 --> 18:33.960
really contending with just how compromise everything already is. The tragic though is to be

18:33.960 --> 18:44.360
lost and broken by despair. The tragic is to be unable to function because you're so thoroughly

18:44.360 --> 18:49.560
depressed when everything seems to be going wrong. But the problem is tragic as you get stuck in

18:49.560 --> 18:55.000
them, completely stuck in them. And the claim here is that it's not that it's better to be

18:55.000 --> 19:03.880
post-tragic as such, but just there is also a state of sort of sensibility available to us that

19:03.880 --> 19:10.440
doesn't have the pre-tragic. Nothing's wrong. Everything will be fine. But nor is it lost forever

19:10.440 --> 19:19.440
in the kind of the implosion of the tragic. It reclaims the agency of the pre-tragic informed by

19:19.440 --> 19:26.840
the understanding of the tragic to live in a way that recognizes that suffering and pain is an

19:26.840 --> 19:35.080
endemic feature of life. Humans screw things up all the time. We can't help it almost. I believe

19:35.080 --> 19:39.920
one of the better definitions of sin for what it's worth is from Francis Spufford. He calls it

19:39.920 --> 19:47.160
the human propensity to fuck things up. And it's a real feature of human life. So the post-tragic

19:47.160 --> 19:54.040
recognizes that as something that we can't escape. There will be no Eden as such. There will still

19:54.040 --> 19:59.760
be wars. There will still be sociopaths. There will still be narcissists. There'll still be corruption.

19:59.760 --> 20:05.560
And yet you don't collapse and despair because of that, because it's not really your work to do to

20:05.560 --> 20:10.760
solve that. That's baked into reality as the oppositional principles that gives rise to creative

20:10.760 --> 20:17.080
possibilities and so on. What the post-tragic's about is rediscovering the beauty on the other side

20:17.120 --> 20:23.320
of the suffering, to see that somehow the soul is formed through those contests, those battles.

20:23.320 --> 20:39.840
