20:40.600 --> 20:49.520
because reason is powerful and good. Science, when it's working well, is important. And we shouldn't

20:49.520 --> 20:54.400
wish these things away. But what is true, and I think Paul Marshall does a particularly good job

20:54.400 --> 21:01.000
at this in his book, Complex Integral Realism, he speaks about the biases of the modern mind.

21:01.000 --> 21:08.160
And what he's doing there is fleshing out Jean Gebster's notion of the evolution of consciousness

21:08.160 --> 21:13.720
and the mind in its mental rational function breaking down and he's spelling it out. And he

21:13.720 --> 21:22.080
speaks about the various kinds of biases, but the essence of it, the way he sums it up, is that the

21:22.080 --> 21:28.520
modern mind got very good at standing back. Again, the term poly crisis, it's all standing back

21:28.520 --> 21:36.880
and looking at it. But it lost its way in terms of looking within, which is more about the depth

21:36.920 --> 21:43.960
of the psyche, the deep interior. And it lost its way in terms of let's say cosmo vision and

21:43.960 --> 21:51.080
metaphysics. It stopped asking, what are our assumptions about the fabric of reality? And those

21:51.080 --> 21:57.400
two moves, the looking within and looking beyond, are the other two meanings of meta, which is why

21:57.400 --> 22:03.680
I think metacrisis is the term to use, because that's the work we have to do. It's like, what is

22:03.720 --> 22:09.160
inside the imaginal realm? What is the psyche? How do we know it better? How do we live through it

22:09.160 --> 22:14.840
so that we have less need of consumer durables to live well, that we don't need to meet our

22:14.840 --> 22:22.720
emotional needs by buying something new necessarily. And at the same time, the sort of broadly liberal

22:22.720 --> 22:28.680
imaginary that says, have your religion if you want, but keep it out of the public realm as far

22:28.680 --> 22:36.360
as you can, doesn't seem to be working very well. It would appear that we need a view of the world

22:36.360 --> 22:48.920
that is altogether more enchanted, more profoundly, I think, personal. It's not like anything goes.

22:48.920 --> 22:55.440
It's not like you surrender your intellect or surrender your critical faculties. It's just

22:55.520 --> 23:01.560
that you realize that the story you've been told about material reality, cause and consequence,

23:01.560 --> 23:08.240
space and time, it's less than the full story. And because it's less than the full story, with

23:08.240 --> 23:15.200
all due discernment, with all due care, with all due critical caution, be open to the possibility

23:15.200 --> 23:20.160
that the world is radically different from the one you imagined. So when I have something like a

23:20.160 --> 23:27.200
serendipity or a feeling that the universe is somehow talking to me, I can explain it away,

23:27.760 --> 23:35.200
but I prefer not to. And I don't have to. The universe may well be enchanted and there may well

23:35.200 --> 23:42.560
be a form of relationship between the cosmos and us that we need to reconnect with and at scale and

23:42.560 --> 23:50.320
quickly so that the major collective action problems we face feel different and they feel

23:50.320 --> 23:56.240
different not just to the niche people who are complaining, but to the powers that be as well.

23:58.720 --> 24:04.560
You can't really know. So in the absence of not being able to know with certainty,

24:05.600 --> 24:09.040
do you opt for a kind of conventional view of how things are

24:09.360 --> 24:19.040
that is still culturally hegemonic? Or do you venture out into other ways of knowing that seem

24:19.920 --> 24:25.040
less socially validated, but perhaps more emotionally rewarding and credible?

24:26.800 --> 24:34.640
And personally, I do the latter. But I do think it's delicate because you could have psychosis,

